node.text: Our Adaptable, Deployable Entry Placement Technology, or ADEPT, is a next-generation heat shield design for delivering jumbo-size payloads to planetary surfaces. Made of 3D woven carbon fabric, it can open like an umbrella and withstands temperatures greater than 3,000 degrees Fahrenheit. In this video, its new seamless “Spiderweave” knit is put to the test at our facility that simulates the intense heating spacecraft experience during atmospheric entry.

node.text:
Vice President Kamala Harris recently spoke with astronauts Dr. Shannon Walker and Dr. Kate Rubins aboard the International Space Station and got to meet Honey, one of our Astrobee robots!
 
The cube-shaped robots will help astronauts reduce time they spend on routine duties, leaving them to focus more on the things that only humans can do in space. Robots like Astrobee will play a significant part in our mission to return to the Moon under the Artemis program by helping maintain spacecraft when astronauts are not aboard. 
 
The vice president also learned about our Micro-16 biology experiment, which uses worms to explore the cause of muscle weakening that astronauts can experience in microgravity. The results could support new therapies to combat the effects of age-related muscle loss on Earth.

Learn more about Astrobee: https://www.nasa.gov/astrobee

Learn more about Micro-16: https://go.nasa.gov/3reoyGQ
 
Video credit: NASA
#nasa #amesresearchcenter #space #robot #astrobee #astronaut #spacestation #artemis

node.text: #NASAatHome Highlight: Taking a guided tour of the International Space Station with astronaut Suni Williams! 👩‍🚀🛰 Watch the full video: https://go.nasa.gov/2USBgMx

node.title: Tour of the International Space Station

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Ames on August 24, 2021. May be an image of sky.

node.text:
Do you even lift? 

We do! Our Revolutionary Vertical Lift Technology project is developing tech for vehicles like air taxis that can take off and land from any spot, as well as hover in place.  Simulations like the one of a vertical lift flying over San Francisco pictured here, can help us determine what makes for a safe, efficient, and comfortable flight. 

Image Credit: NASA 
Learn more: go.nasa.gov/3sG2aaY 

#NASA #NASAAmesResearchCenter #Aeronautics #Aviation #Helicopters #Aircraft  #Simulators #Drones #AirTaxis

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Ames on August 23, 2021.

node.text:
🎶 There’s a dazzling haze, a mysterious way about you… 🎶 
 
Millions of miles away, planet Saturn still captures us in a daze. A series of dark and light cloud bands and an atmospheric haze surround this jewel of our solar system.
 
Image credit: NASA 
#NASA #AmesResearchCenter #Saturn #Space #SolarSystem

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Ames on August 22, 2021. May be an image of helicopter and outdoors.

node.text:
Once in a blue moon, a season has four full Moons instead of three. 
 
This weekend’s full Moon is the third of the summer, known as a "Blue Moon" by the old definition.
 
This composite image of a Blue Moon and our Rotocraft Aircrew System Airborn Laboratory UH-60 Blackhawk helicopter was taken in 1996 at our Silicon Valley Center. 
 
Image credit: NASA/Dominic Hart 
Learn more: https://go.nasa.gov/3giOLkn
 
#NASA #AmesResearchCenter #FullMoon #Moon #Helicopter #Blackhawk #Rotorcraft #Aircraft

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Ames on August 19, 2021.

node.text:
To make history, you need the Wright stuff! 

Today, we celebrate #NationalAviationDay on what would be Orville Wright’s 150th birthday. 

Nearly a century after its inaugural flight, a replica of the Wright brothers’ first plane, the Wright Flyer, joined the list of aircraft that have been in our wind tunnels. 

Wind tunnels move air past a stationary object, making it seem like the object is flying. This helps researchers observe the stability and aerodynamics of aircraft, spacecraft, and related components before they ever take to the sky.
 
Image credit: NASA/Tom Trower 
Learn more: www.nasa.gov/ames/wind-tunnels

#WrightFlyer #WindTunnels #NASA #AmesResearchCenter #Aircraft

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Ames on August 18, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'RANGESO TWO OF TURBOJET AIRPLANES Subsonic Supersonic Ranr Heat- resistant structures Present structures 2000'.

node.text:
Look familiar? 

The red v-shape in our logo represents the “aeronautics” in National Aeronautics and Space Administration (@NASA). Did you know that it was inspired by a supersonic wing design from our center when we were still part of the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics, aka the NACA? 
 
The logo's symbol is a stylization of an actual NACA-designed wing concept for supersonic flight at Mach 3. It was on display when James Modarelli, who designed the agency’s logo, came to visit in 1958.

Image credit: NACA
Learn more: go.nasa.gov/3jYXtVT

#NASA #NACA #AmesResearchCenter #NationalAviationDay #Aircraft

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Ames on August 17, 2021. May be an image of 1 person.

node.text:
It can be hard to “x-plane” how we test supersonic aircraft. 

But Don Durston, can do it! He leads the wind tunnel testing of our X-59 Quiet SuperSonic Technology X-plane. The X-59 is our first purpose-built, supersonic X-plane in decades, and its unique shape and set of technologies reduce the loudness of a sonic boom to a gentle thump! 

The plane is on track to be completed by the end of 2021, and will begin test flights in 2022. 

Image Credit: NASA/Dominic Hart 
Learn more: https://go.nasa.gov/37UAYvr 

#Aircraft #X59 #XPlane #NASA #AmesResearchCenter

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Ames on August 16, 2021. May be a closeup of African daisy and nature.

node.text:
What a re-leaf that plants need space to grow! 🌱✨

From hearty veggies like lettuce and peppers to vibrant flowers like zinnias, the crews aboard the International Space Station (@iss) have spent years testing plant growth in microgravity. 

Image Credit: NASA/Scott Kelly 
Learn more: https://go.nasa.gov/3ABXwxI 

#NASAAmesResearchCenter #NASA #SpaceStation #Space #zinnias #astronauts #flowers

node.text: Our Adaptable, Deployable Entry Placement Technology, or ADEPT, is a next-generation heat shield design for delivering jumbo-size payloads to planetary surfaces. Made of 3D woven carbon fabric, it can open like an umbrella and withstands temperatures greater than 3,000 degrees Fahrenheit. In this video, its new seamless “Spiderweave” knit is put to the test at our facility that simulates the intense heating spacecraft experience during atmospheric entry.

node.text:
We left our ❤️ in San Francisco.

The City by the Bay is just north of our Silicon Valley center, and with #NationalAviationDay on the horizon we are reminiscing over some scenic flights we have done around San Francisco’s iconic sights. Do you recognize them?

[1]: CV-990 (NASA 712) Galileo II aircraft in flight over the Golden Gate Bridge in 1975. 
Image credit: NASA/George Olczak

[2]: ER-2 (NASA 708) and U-2 (NASA 709) in formation over Alcatraz Island in 1988. 
Image credit: NASA/Eric James

[3]: DC-8 (NASA 717) in flight over downtown San Francisco in 1991.
Image credit: NASA/Eric James 

[4]: C-130 (NASA 707) in flight over Golden Gate Bridge in 1991. 
Image credit: NASA/Ed Schilling

node.text:
This robot has got you covered.
 
Our #Astrobee Bumble detected an anomaly aboard the International Space Station (@iss) — part of a simulation to test the robot’s response to a potentially dangerous situation. 
 
The exercise marked the end of the first phase of testing for the Integrated System for Autonomous and Adaptive Caretaking system, or ISAAC, software. The technology is designed to enable autonomous operations of a spacecraft’s systems including both general maintenance and responding to crises — even when no crew is around. It could be vital for future deep space exploration and managing Gateway, the Artemis (@NASAArtemis) program’s lunar outpost. 
 
Image credit: NASA 
Learn more: go.nasa.gov/2XnHIAl
 
#Astrobee #InternationalSpaceStation #Robots #AmesResearchCenter #nasa #Artemis #NASAGateway

node.text:
We are celebrating our stellar space telescopes with groovy new posters! 

You can choose our Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite, or TESS, which has been hunting the skies since 2018 and monitoring more than 200,000 pre-selected stars in that time. Or you can commemorate the Kepler space telescope, which discovered more than 2,600 planets outside our solar system after nine years in deep space!

Image credit for [1]: NASA
Image credit for [2-4]: NASA/JPL-Caltech
